text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Plosives in Indian Languages%0a:Author: nithyas%0a:Original: [[Articles.IndianAccentInTVShows|IndianAccentInTVShows]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Spencer_L|Spencer_L]]%0a:Section: D%0a:Completed: 23.04.2021 - 21:31%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-021110-916090#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:11-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-021110-916090#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI think the "creation" of an Indian accent in TV shows by pronouncing the [d] and [t] sounds further back in the mouth than the conventional sounds in Standard American English is an interesting phenomenon that mimics the Indian accent pretty well.%0a%0aHowever, as a native speaker of an Indian language (Tamil), I want to potentially push back on this idea that the [d] and [t] sounds do not exist in Indian languages (at least in the same way they exist in American English, which is the alveolar or dental plosive). You mention that typically, the [d] and [t] sounds in Indian dialects of English involve pronouncing the consonant further back in the sound, and this is largely due to the fact that the [d] and [t] sounds in Indian languages are typically pronounced further back in the mouth. I think this is certainly true, and can think of numerous examples ("dabba" - box, "kadavul" - god, etc.), but I'm not sure if the claim that alveolar and dental plosives cease to exist altogether is true. The reason for this is there are many words I can think of where my natural pronunciation of the [d] or [t] sound in the word is in fact alveolar and not further back ("pattasu" - firework, "padam" - movie). However, I'm not entirely sure if this is a consequence of my own pronunciation, and it is worth noting that the pronunciations of the words I listed are not audibly altered if they are pronounced as retroflex rather than alveolar. Additionally, it is hard to verify by looking up transcriptions for these words since the scripts for these languages are different, so you may very well be correct, but it is definitely an interesting thing to think about.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
